<collectingRegion id="A60FF8795140BF3CFDECD81EFCB90D16" box="[628,800,562,588]" country="Mexico" name="Baja California" pageId="4" pageNumber="173">Baja California</collectingRegion>
and off Cabo San Lucas, in the southern Gulf of 
<collectingRegion id="A60FF8795140BF3CFADCD81EFF250D2A" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="4" pageNumber="173">California</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="1CDC760B5140BF3CFF5FD87AFE840D2A" box="[199,285,598,624]" name="Mexico" pageId="4" pageNumber="173">Mexico</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="005A4B6A5140BF3CFEB3D87AFDCE0D2B" author="Brusca, R. C. &amp; Hendrickx, M. E." box="[299,599,598,625]" pageId="4" pageNumber="173" pagination="139 - 154" refId="ref14339" refString="Brusca, R. C. &amp; Hendrickx, M. E. (2005) Cap. 12. Crustacea 4. Lophogastrida, Mysida, Amphipoda, Tanaidacea &amp; Cumacea. In: Hendrickx, M. E., Brusca, R. C. &amp; Findley L. T. (Eds.), A Distributional Checklist of the Macrofauna of the Gulf of California, Mexico. Part I. Invertebrates. [Listado y Distribucion de la Macrofauna del Golfo de California, Mexico, Parte I. Invertebrados]. Arizona-Sonora Desert Museum, Tucson, Arizona, pp. 139 - 154." type="book chapter" year="2005">Brusca &amp; Hendrickx 2005</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="005A4B6A5140BF3CFDFAD87AFCC70D2A" author="Garcia Madrigal, M. S." box="[610,862,598,624]" pageId="4" pageNumber="173" pagination="63 - 195" refId="ref14782" refString="Garcia Madrigal, M. S. (2007) Annotated checklist of the amphipods (Peracarida: Amphipoda) from the tropical eastern Pacific. Contributions to the Study of East Pacific Crustaceans, 4 (2), 63 - 195." type="journal article" year="2007">García Madrigal 2007</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2CD165105140BF3CFF5FD856FDC00CEE" pageId="4" pageNumber="173" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="6474369B5140BF3CFF5FD856FF440C7E" blockId="4.[151,1437,453,948]" pageId="4" pageNumber="173">
<emphasis id="56BFEA895140BF3CFF5FD856FEAD0DCE" bold="true" box="[199,308,634,660]" pageId="4" pageNumber="173">Remarks</emphasis>
. Commonly found in the Gulf of 
<collectingRegion id="A60FF8795140BF3CFD2CD856FCB10DCE" box="[692,808,634,660]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="4" pageNumber="173">California</collectingRegion>
, particularly in the southern part (
<bibRefCitation id="005A4B6A5140BF3CFB30D856FA090DCE" author="Siegel-Causey, D." box="[1192,1424,634,660]" pageId="4" pageNumber="173" refId="ref16354" refString="Siegel-Causey, D. (1982) Factors determining the distribution of hyperiid Amphipoda in the Gulf of California. Ph. D. Thesis, University of Arizona, Tucson, Arizona, 535 pp." type="book" year="1982">Siegel-Causey 1982</bibRefCitation>
). Other records in the Gulf of 
<collectingRegion id="A60FF8795140BF3CFE48D8B2FDDB0DE2" box="[464,578,670,696]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="4" pageNumber="173">California</collectingRegion>
are from 
<geoCoordinate id="01FF505C5140BF3CFD34D8B2FCA10DE3" box="[684,824,670,697]" degrees="23" direction="north" minutes="54" orientation="latitude" pageId="4" pageNumber="173" precision="15" seconds="27" value="23.9075">23°54’27”N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="01FF505C5140BF3CFCDAD8B2FC440DE2" box="[834,989,670,696]" degrees="111" direction="west" minutes="20" orientation="longitude" pageId="4" pageNumber="173" precision="15" seconds="21" value="-111.33917">111°20’21”W</geoCoordinate>
and 
<geoCoordinate id="01FF505C5140BF3CFB89D8B2FB040DE3" box="[1041,1181,670,697]" degrees="23" direction="north" minutes="50" orientation="latitude" pageId="4" pageNumber="173" precision="15" seconds="30" value="23.841667">23°50’30”N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="01FF505C5140BF3CFB30D8B2FADA0DE3" box="[1192,1347,670,697]" degrees="111" direction="west" minutes="15" orientation="longitude" pageId="4" pageNumber="173" precision="15" seconds="45" value="-111.2625">111°15’45”W</geoCoordinate>
(
<bibRefCitation id="005A4B6A5140BF3CFAC8D8B2FED00D86" author="Garcia Madrigal, M. S." pageId="4" pageNumber="173" pagination="63 - 195" refId="ref14782" refString="Garcia Madrigal, M. S. (2007) Annotated checklist of the amphipods (Peracarida: Amphipoda) from the tropical eastern Pacific. Contributions to the Study of East Pacific Crustaceans, 4 (2), 63 - 195." type="journal article" year="2007">García Madrigal, 2007</bibRefCitation>
). Mostly epipelagic and partly mesopelagic (surface to 
<quantity id="A3339B7E5140BF3CFC2ED8EEFBA10D86" box="[950,1080,706,732]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="173" unit="m" value="250.0" valueMax="300.0" valueMin="200.0">200‒300 m</quantity>
), occasionally deeper (
<quantity id="A3339B7E5140BF3CFAA0D8EEFF370C5A" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="173" unit="m" value="550.0" valueMax="600.0" valueMin="500.0">500‒600 m</quantity>
) (
<bibRefCitation id="005A4B6A5140BF3CFF5DD8CAFE560C5B" author="Vinogradov, M. E. &amp; Volkov, A. F. &amp; Semenova, T. N." box="[197,463,742,769]" pageId="4" pageNumber="173" refId="ref16750" refString="Vinogradov, M. E., Volkov, A. F. &amp; Semenova, T. N. (1996) Hyperiid amphipods (Amphipoda, Hyperiidea) of the world oceans. Oxonian Press Pvt. Ltd., New Delhi, 632 pp." type="book" year="1996">
Vinogradov 
<emphasis id="56BFEA895140BF3CFECBD8CBFE150C5A" box="[339,396,742,768]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="173">et al.</emphasis>
1996
</bibRefCitation>
). According to 
<bibRefCitation id="005A4B6A5140BF3CFDE4D8CAFC1E0C5A" author="Garcia Madrigal, M. S." box="[636,903,742,768]" pageId="4" pageNumber="173" pagination="63 - 195" refId="ref14782" refString="Garcia Madrigal, M. S. (2007) Annotated checklist of the amphipods (Peracarida: Amphipoda) from the tropical eastern Pacific. Contributions to the Study of East Pacific Crustaceans, 4 (2), 63 - 195." type="journal article" year="2007">García Madrigal (2007)</bibRefCitation>
this species occurs between surface and 
<quantity id="A3339B7E5140BF3CFACDD8CAFA050C5A" box="[1365,1436,742,768]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.8" pageId="4" pageNumber="173" unit="m" value="680.0">680 m</quantity>
depth.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6474369B5140BF3CFF5FD902FDC00CEE" blockId="4.[151,1437,453,948]" pageId="4" pageNumber="173">
The specimens examined are partially damaged and somewhat transparent, but shows the main distinctive characteristic of the species, i.e., eyes limited to the upper part of the head, and dactyls of PV to PVII shorter than in 
<taxonomicName id="A3CB4D185140BF3CFF0FD95BFE860CCA" baseAuthorityName="Stebbing" baseAuthorityYear="1888" box="[151,287,886,912]" class="Malacostraca" family="Lestrigonidae" genus="Hyperioides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="4" pageNumber="173" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sibaginis">
<emphasis id="56BFEA895140BF3CFF0FD95BFE860CCA" box="[151,287,886,912]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="173">H. sibaginis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, its only known congener. Also, the 3-segmented peduncle of antennae 1 and 2 is characteristic of this species and observable in our specimen.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
